00:40:02.290 --> 00:40:05.490
And if you're focusing like
in Egypt on replacing Mubarak,

00:40:05.490 --> 00:40:08.380
then you maybe end up
with Sisi, who is either

00:40:08.380 --> 00:40:10.690
same or worse as Mubarak.

00:40:10.690 --> 00:40:14.030
Whereas if we were building a
struggle on the values in terms

00:40:14.030 --> 00:40:16.850
of, this is what we stand
for, it is very likely

00:40:16.850 --> 00:40:19.590
that these values will
prevail on the society whoever

00:40:19.590 --> 00:40:23.710
sits on the top of the pyramid.

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:26.430
On the topic of
Stratfor and leaks,

00:40:26.430 --> 00:40:28.700
I've done one presentation
with these guys, which

00:40:28.700 --> 00:40:31.640
looks very much like
this, though the venue was

00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:33.870
a little bit less fancy.

00:40:33.870 --> 00:40:36.090
And I have a friend
working there.

00:40:36.090 --> 00:40:41.730
And I think the big idea of
evil secret services being

00:40:41.730 --> 00:40:45.360
around anything is exactly
the public narrative

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:47.890
we want to kill with this book.

00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:51.050
And I think the very obsession
with conspiracy theories

00:40:51.050 --> 00:40:53.890
and the fact that
everybody believes

00:40:53.890 --> 00:40:57.760
that there is this super
successful secret service who

00:40:57.760 --> 00:41:00.060
are pulling the
strings everywhere

00:41:00.060 --> 00:41:01.990
and understand the
stuff, they often

00:41:01.990 --> 00:41:03.840
can't find their own nose.

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:08.250
So in my experience, I would
speak with about everybody.

00:41:08.250 --> 00:41:10.240
I will give a
presentation to CIA.

00:41:10.240 --> 00:41:12.190
I will give a
presentation to KGB.

00:41:12.190 --> 00:41:15.040
I would give the
presentation to FSB.

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:17.040
And I'll give the
presentation to Google.

00:41:17.040 --> 00:41:23.130
If there is one single
person in the audience

00:41:23.130 --> 00:41:25.560
I can persuade in an
organization like Stratfor

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:30.390
or CIA that it is the people
who make the change, not

00:41:30.390 --> 00:41:34.410
the military, that it is the
people you should invest into,

00:41:34.410 --> 00:41:39.414
not elites, and the only way
to do the durable change is

00:41:39.414 --> 00:41:41.330
actually to work with
the people on the ground

00:41:41.330 --> 00:41:42.954
and appreciate the
people on the ground

00:41:42.954 --> 00:41:46.880
and empower the people on the
ground, I would rather do that.

00:41:46.880 --> 00:41:49.310
So that's my point of view.

00:41:49.310 --> 00:41:52.330
I will speak to the
very devil in order

00:41:52.330 --> 00:41:56.080
to persuade the devil that
things should be changed.

00:41:56.080 --> 00:41:58.050
And last but not of
least importance--

00:41:58.050 --> 00:41:59.990
to this question of technology.

00:41:59.990 --> 00:42:02.140
And I spent 20 minutes
speaking with Dan

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:04.270
about this in the podcast.

00:42:04.270 --> 00:42:05.870
I will try to be fast.

00:42:05.870 --> 00:42:09.240
Modern technology is super
effective in some kind

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:10.230
of stuff.

00:42:10.230 --> 00:42:13.050
And there's this super
cool guy call Clay Shirky.

00:42:13.050 --> 00:42:16.590
And you should watch his talk
called "Here Comes Everybody."

00:42:16.590 --> 00:42:19.900
He's very, very enthusiastic
about how the technology can

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:21.586
bring about the mobilization.

00:42:21.586 --> 00:42:23.210
And we had a great
discussion about it.

00:42:23.210 --> 00:42:26.555
And I think technology does
three things very well.

00:42:26.555 --> 00:42:30.380
It makes thing faster,
cheaper, more safe.

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:34.440
B, it puts a huge
price tag on violence

00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:35.490
over the demonstrators.

00:42:35.490 --> 00:42:38.167
Because even in a low-tech
society like Bahrain,

00:42:38.167 --> 00:42:39.250
you see the demonstration.

00:42:39.250 --> 00:42:42.070
There's like 50 people taping.

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:45.870
So it would be very difficult
to hide any kind of attempt

00:42:45.870 --> 00:42:48.460
to do something nasty.

00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:51.100
And last but not of least
importance in my case,

00:42:51.100 --> 00:42:53.040
it enables you to learn.

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:56.245
So where this is the horizontal
learning, online learning,

00:42:56.245 --> 00:43:00.250
this enables activists to
connect on the learning point.

00:43:00.250 --> 00:43:02.120
Also, technology comes
with a big price.

00:43:02.120 --> 00:43:03.440
First, we get too obsessed.

00:43:03.440 --> 00:43:07.420
In the technological world,
as my co-writer Matt Miller

00:43:07.420 --> 00:43:10.680
would say, everything is
about the shares and clicks.

00:43:10.680 --> 00:43:13.070
So if you have a really
cool viral video where

00:43:13.070 --> 00:43:16.104
you're mocking your dictator,
and you get 5 million clicks,

00:43:16.104 --> 00:43:17.770
then you really think
that you're really

00:43:17.770 --> 00:43:19.480
on the top of the pyramid.

00:43:19.480 --> 00:43:22.990
And that brings you to
the Kony 2012 campaign,

00:43:22.990 --> 00:43:25.590
which was probably the most
successful public awareness

00:43:25.590 --> 00:43:27.785
raising online campaign ever.

00:43:27.785 --> 00:43:30.130
But Kony, where is Kony?

00:43:30.130 --> 00:43:33.060
He's in Uganda with
his soldiers army.

00:43:33.060 --> 00:43:35.520
OK, so when you're
looking at the effects,

00:43:35.520 --> 00:43:38.280
effects should be made
in the real world,

00:43:38.280 --> 00:43:40.690
rather than being too
obsessed with the effects

00:43:40.690 --> 00:43:42.355
in the virtual world.

00:43:42.355 --> 00:43:43.855
We call this
phenomenon clicktivism.

00:43:43.855 --> 00:43:46.910
And it often says, you know,
I clicked on this page.

00:43:46.910 --> 00:43:50.860
I save one polar bear every
day like over my coffee.

00:43:50.860 --> 00:43:52.770
But the one which
I really, really

00:43:52.770 --> 00:43:56.430
consider dangerous, and
dangerous misunderstanding,

00:43:56.430 --> 00:44:00.010
I think, is the phenomenon
we call occupyism.

00:44:00.010 --> 00:44:03.860
It has nothing to do with the
social values of Occupy Wall

00:44:03.860 --> 00:44:04.520
Street.

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:08.010
It has to do with the
very, very stupid intention

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:12.240
of the movements to copy/paste
the most dangerous, most

00:44:12.240 --> 00:44:15.065
demanding, and very,
very risky tactics

00:44:15.065 --> 00:44:17.780
of occupying symbolic
public space.

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:19.770
We could see this in Hong Kong.

00:44:19.770 --> 00:44:21.680
We want to protest,
we must occupy.

00:44:21.680 --> 00:44:23.180
Why the hell we must occupy?

00:44:23.180 --> 00:44:25.160
There's so many other
things we can do.

00:44:25.160 --> 00:44:26.010
We can whistle.

00:44:26.010 --> 00:44:27.190
We can hit pots and pans.

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:28.240
We can wear symbols.

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:29.860
We can organize parties.

00:44:29.860 --> 00:44:30.507
We can vote.

00:44:30.507 --> 00:44:31.340
We can do petitions.

00:44:31.340 --> 00:44:33.360
There's around 200
different things

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:38.300
we can do instead of putting
all of our parts into one place

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:40.160
and waiting for police to come.

00:44:40.160 --> 00:44:43.730
Plus, if we repeat this every
day, we become predictable.

00:44:43.730 --> 00:44:45.630
Plus, if we repeat
this every day,

00:44:45.630 --> 00:44:48.920
where will the people go
to the toilet on day seven?

00:44:48.920 --> 00:44:51.660
How is this square going
to look on day nine?

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:54.780
How the people will get
thrilled once the rain starts.

00:44:54.780 --> 00:44:57.484
What about the rugby game?

00:44:57.484 --> 00:44:58.650
People don't think about it.

00:44:58.650 --> 00:44:59.580
They get too thrilled.

00:44:59.580 --> 00:45:03.770
But I think it's a seduction
of the new media, which

00:45:03.770 --> 00:45:08.860
enables you to gather
your number too fast.

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:12.420
It's like one thing if you
can assemble numbers quickly.

00:45:12.420 --> 00:45:15.800
But if you assemble these
numbers before you're ready,

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:18.080
it's also a very,
very big threat,

00:45:18.080 --> 00:45:20.430
not only because there will
be five drunk idiots who

00:45:20.430 --> 00:45:22.500
will start throwing
Molotovs and destroy

00:45:22.500 --> 00:45:25.250
your beautiful demonstration,
but because occupation

00:45:25.250 --> 00:45:27.900
is such a risky and
demanding tactic.

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:31.730
And you want this tactic not
before you're ready, only

00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:32.480
at the end game.

00:45:32.480 --> 00:45:35.230
Then you do the
concentration tactics.

